  Public Hearing Notice Land Use Development Application
  
  Project Title: Sky Retreat at Westwater rezone for Overnight Accommodations Overlay (OAO)- Campground district
  
  Project Address: Grand County parcel no. 04-0025-0105 (Within Section 16, T20S, R25E, SLB&M)
  
  Project Description: The application is for an OAO-/Campground rezone for a 40 acre parcel in the Westwater area. The applicant proposes developing an off-grid educational retreat centered on astronomy. The proposal includes plans for 16 cabins, one common building with communal kitchen and two bathhouses as well as two observation areas for stargazing. The applicant has processed the rezone application in accordance with State and County regulation.
  
  Project Applicant: TBE,LLC is the property owner and the applicant
  
  Public Hearing Information County Commission
  
  Date: Tuesday, December 7th, 2021
  
  Time: 4:00 PM or later
  
  Location: Virtual on zoom with 214317
  
  Meeting ID: 851 7082 0571 Password:
  
  Agenda Packet: [www.grandcountyutah.net/AgendaCenter](http://www.grandcountyutah.net/AgendaCenter)
  
  For more information contact the Grand County Planning & Zoning Department 125 E. Center St. Moab, Utah 84532 435-259-1343
  
  A public hearing is a statutory requirement for some land use decisions. At a public hearing, members of the public are provided a reasonable opportunity to comment on the subject of the hearing.
  
  * * *
  
  Proposed Project & Information Provided by Applicant
  
  The Sky Retreat at Westwater (henceforth, "the retreat") is conceived to be a small off-grid development which combines the attributes of a campground with the outreach facets of astronomy observatories and science museums. The retreat is intended for all audiences - no prior knowledge of astronomy is required to visit and enjoy the night sky. The retreat will be unique among astronomy destinations in that visitors can stay up late and then recuperate on site without making long, bleary-eyed drives to their home or city-based overnight accommodations.
  
  The founder of the retreat, Mike Toomey, has been a Lifetime Member of the International Dark Sky Association since 1998 (addendum 1). He has been involved in astronomy outreach at museums, planetaria and observatories for 24 years. He serves on the board of two philanthropic foundations benefiting natural sciences. These interests and expertise have inspired the concept for the Sky Retreat at Westwater.
  
  The development site for the retreat requires a unique set of criteria. The location must be reasonably accessible yet in a relatively remote, undeveloped area with minimal light pollution. The Westwater area possesses these qualities.
  
  Impacts and Benefits
  
  The Sky Retreat at Westwater will offer guests an opportunity to enjoy Grand County's dark skies and open spaces with negligible impact to vicinities around Moab. The remote location makes day trips to Moab unlikely; a round-trip would require no less than 3 hours. Guests will be encouraged to arrive at the retreat with the provisions necessary for the duration of their stay, but if additional supplies are needed, a round trip to Fruita will take half the time. (addendum 2)
  
  The retreat will be consistent and compatible with land use in the area. The parcel under consideration lies within a small pocket of private land parcels which are, for the most part, surrounded by BLM. There has been little development in the area and none has occurred on the properties immediately adjacent to this parcel. Adjoining landowners have demonstrated that recreation is the best use of properties in the vicinity.
  
  Commitment to Sustainability
  
  Development of the retreat will provide beneficial diversity in recreational opportunities and expanded access to natural open spaces. The environs of Grand County are a popular destination for outdoor enthusiasts but they can sometimes be inhospitable. The retreat would expand access for visitors to spend time in a natural environment.
  
  * * *
  
  Vicinity Map
