  R. Approving correspondence to the Bureau of Land Management (BLM) regarding the BLM’s Labyrinth Canyon / Gemini Bridges Travel Management Plan (Commissioner Walker)
  **Presentation**
  
  12/22/21 Page 7 of 11
  
  * * *
  
  DocuSign Envelope ID: 9F70BEA7-FB48-4DDC-A849-D1C4C0B8806E
  
  Sarah discussed the proposed letters to the BLM regarding the Environmental Assessment (EA) and Travel Management Plan for Gemini Bridges and Labyrinth Canyon. Sarah discussed the potential user conflicts in the areas and route recommendations. Sarah noted the intent is not to enable broad closures, but to encourage the BLM to assess common uses in the areas and create a management plan that reduces potential user conflict. Sarah noted the idea of “no net loss” of roads is incompatible with increased use.
  
  Kevin noted the letters are due by December 10 th . Sarah noted the county is not driving the process, but merely providing input. Trish suggested the county is not attempting to limit any input or discouraging other groups from commenting on the plan. Kevin noted the specific points of comment in this letter are not substantially different than letters sent from the County in the past. Kevin noted the debates have been going on for 30+ years, but few user groups are actually willing to negotiate effectively. Kevin noted the letter is not intended as an attack to motorized users at all, but an attempt at fair use for diverse groups. Kevin suggested that increased use generally comes with increased rules and regulations.
  
  Sarah noted the letter addresses requests from the BLM for more specific suggestions. Mary noted there are roads almost everywhere, and closing select roads in certain areas is likely appropriate in some cases. Trish discussed use impacts to wildlife and wildscapes by all users, and noted all user groups have some impact. Trish noted the importance of multiple uses and varied uses and balance in all user groups. Kevin noted the list of routes offered is for assessment, not actual closure. Kevin noted the importance of keeping options open in the future for use assessments, and suggested the BLM study a wide range of alternatives.
  
  Evan noted the importance of access while respecting the landscape and keeping a future options open. Evan noted one viable option put forward by the BLM is the “do nothing” option.
  
  Jacques thanked all the commenters from the motorized community. Jacques noted while he doesn’t support all the closures, the ability to study the routes and plan and anticipate for future use is important. Kevin discussed some of the differences between perceived and actual user conflicts. Sarah noted there are other options for management in areas with high user conflict.
  
